We compare the proposed GFL-APPNP to baseline models including GCN, GAT, and GraphSAGE under the DNC setting described in ¬ß¬ß\S5.1.
For synthetic data, we use contextual Stochastic Block Models (cSBMs) [38] to generate synthetic graphs with approximately two equal-size classes. For real-world data, we use subgraphs of Cora [39], namely subCora, due to the limitation of computational resources. The details of the generation of synthetic graphs by cSBMs and the generation of subCora graphs are provided in Appendix D.2.
For the proposed GFL-APPNP, we use a two-layer MLP with 646464 hidden units. Œ±ùõº\alpha is chosen to be 0.10.10.1 and the total number of steps for personalized propagation MùëÄM is set as 101010, following the same configuration as it in the [40] for the APPNP model. IùêºI is set to be {1,10,20,50}1102050\{1,10,20,50\}. SGD is applied as our optimizer with the optimized learning rate. Baseline models including GCN, GAT, and GraphSAGE follow the same design of the well-optimized hyperparameters from [41, 42, 43]. The details for all models are provided in Appendix D.3.
Table 1 and the first two columns of Figure 3 show that our method of different IùêºI can match the performance of the vanilla APPNP on both synthetic graphs and subCora graphs. Our method rivals baseline models based on Table 1.

We also conduct experiments under the SNC setting described in ¬ß¬ß\S5.1 to test the robustness of GFL-APPNP. As we know, current graph machine learning models are not designed for the SNC task. Therefore our experiment will focus on the proposed GFL-APPNP.
The original cSBMs can not be used to generate data for this task since they are not designed to generate graphs whose nodes have multiple features. We modify the original cSBMs to generate distributions for each client. Details about the modifications for the SNC task are available in Appendix D.2. Similar to ¬ß¬ß\S6.1, we use the same hyperparameters and the same number of updates. The third column of Figure 3 and additional Table 2 provided in Appendix D.4 show that our method is valid for solving the SNC task.

references: Moreover, we also investigated the effect of the standard deviation of the noise on the test set accuracy and the effect of IùêºI when we fix the noise strategy and standard deviation of the noise. Figure 6 shows that when we fix the noise strategy and standard deviation of the noise. A larger standard deviation for the Gaussian noise will result in worse performance (larger loss and higher variation) during training as well as validation. This matches the general situation when applying DP-based privacy-preserving strategies. Also, one can conclude that larger IùêºI will result in a larger final validation loss which is more significant, while a larger standard deviation of the noise is applied. Figure 7 shows that in general, when we fix the noise strategy and IùêºI, a larger standard deviation will lead to lower average test set accuracy. As one may expect, there is a trade-off between performance and privacy protection, matching the results of DP-based methods. But even with a relatively large standard deviation, the average test accuracy is still competitive compared with all other cases. This reflects that DP-based optimization is applicable under the proposed GFL setting. The exact numbers of test accuracy can be found in Table 3.
